  Special: This spell will cancel all Illusion/Phantasm spells of 5th level and lower within its area of effect.

Weight: 1~

@8374 = ~This wardstone is, in fact, an ioun stone. It appears as a void of darkness, absorbing light from the space around it. Its exact shape is difficult to discern, shrouded as it is in shadow.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Immunity to blindness
– Hide in the Shadows: +5%
– +2 Armor class vs. all spectral undead and shadow dragons
– +3% physical damage resistance (Shadowdancers and Dark Soul monks only)

Weight: 1~

@8390 = ~The Mist of Shadows were an elite group of elven Rangers that roamed the Cormanthor wood and were the bane of bandits and monsters alike. This particular armor was worn by Indeera Lakhan, one of the group's most highly decorated officers and second in command. The suit is named for her, though how it came to part her company is unknown.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Armor Class: +1 bonus for rangers, elves, and half-elves
– Hiding ability: +15% (rangers only)

Armor Class: 6 (8 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 4 Strength

Weight: 5~

@8400 = ~Karajah was Calimshan's undisputed champion of pit fighting for a full decade, seemingly unbeatable in the arena. Wearing only a thin leather armor and spiked gauntlets, he would pummel his foes to the ground, impervious to their blows. He attributed his success to the mobility his light armor afforded him, though some suspected there was more to it. Eventually, it was revealed that his armor was heavily enchanted, granting him unnatural resilience. Outraged by the deception, angry spectators threw him into the pit with a club-wielding ogre. The beast managed to break all of Karajah's bones, but the armor remained as good as new...

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Movement rate increases by a factor of 3
– Crushing damage resistance: +10%
– Crushing damage dealt: +8%

Armor Class: 5 (2 vs. crushing, 7 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 3 Strength

Weight: 4~

@8410 = ~Originally blessed by Shar, this armor has a long and interesting history. Only the greatest of thieves have ever owned this heavily enchanted armor. The essence of night has been woven into the dark set of armor so that it feels like normal armor but encloses the wearer in a mass of twisting shadows.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Hide In Shadows: +25%
– Nondetection and immunity to divinations except for True Sight
– At night: become shrouded in shadows, regenerating 1 HP per round. Additionally, each time the wearer is hit, they have a 12% chance of fading as per the Improved Invisibility spell for 4 rounds. This may only trigger once per turn.
– +5% universal damage resistance (thieves only)

Charge abilities:
– Shadow Door cast at level 20 once per day
  Special: Caster is under the effects of Improved Invisibility for 2 turns

– Shadowstep three times per day
  Special: Caster briefly steps into the Shadow Plane and returns to the Material Plane at the desired location as per the Shadowdancer ability

Armor Class: 3 (5 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 3 Strength

Weight: 5~

@8411 = ~Embraced by shadows~

@8420 = ~This ghastly armor was taken from an orc camp destroyed by barbarians. Instead of standard metal rivets, like normal studded leather, this orc leather is instead laced with hundreds of fire-hardened bones. Finger bones, ribs, and skulls cover the armor, acting much like the traditional metal rivets. Powerful orcish enchantments give the armor special resistance to missile attacks, but its grotesque appearance tends to unsettle and alienate others.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Charisma: -2
– +10% resistance to missile damage (double if wearer is half-orc)
– +10 Hit Points (half-orc only)
– +1 melee damage (half-orc only)

Armor Class: 4 (2 vs. slashing, 3 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 6 Strength

Weight: 7~

@8425 = ~A clever thief, Damien Oneknife always tried to gain from the assets of his enemies, no matter the circumstances. After an intense battle with several ghouls in which two of his companions perished, Damien decided to even the odds in future encounters. He skinned one of the undead creatures and brought the hide to a halfling armorer talented in enchanting leather. When the suit was finished, it was magically protective against physical attacks and paralysis. Not very epic perhaps, but practical.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Immunity to paralysis, hold, and stun effects
– Save vs. Death: +3

Armor Class: 4 (6 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 3 Strength

Weight: 4~

@8430 = ~Enchanted ebony rivets adorn the black leather of this armor. Umberlee the Sea Queen granted this armor to Dami Darn, a rogue who slew the conjurer Looxil. The assassination pleased Umberlee, for Looxil had betrayed her in years past. Dami Darn died years later, a knife to the back from her successor in the thieves' guild.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Cold Resistance: +30%
– Electric Resistance: +30%
– Umberlee's boon gives the user a 18% chance per ranged or melee hit to deal 1d4 cold damage, electric damage, or both

Armor Class: 3 (1 vs. slashing, 2 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 6 Strength

Weight: 7~

@8440 = ~This armor is infamous not for its advantages, but for the betrayal it enabled. Raroh, a master assassin, gifted it to Avlorm, a rising member of his guild. The armor's unique properties—granting resilience and the power to poison weapons—were overshadowed by a fatal flaw: it made the wearer dangerously vulnerable to poison. When Avlorm’s ambition became a threat, Raroh exploited this weakness, using the very armor he had given as a tool to eliminate his rival.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Save vs. Death: -3
– All other saves: +1
– Weakness to poison: -50%
– Poison damage: +100%

Charge abilities:
– Poison Weapon once per day
  Special: Poison your weapon as per the Assassin's ability for 5 rounds

Armor Class: 2 (0 vs. slashing, 1 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 6 Strength

Weight: 6~

@8450 = ~This heavy and thick bear hide is all that remains of the fabled Aeger. Several hundred years ago, the Aeger, a giant bear, terrorized hundreds of small villages up and down the Sword Coast. The bear was invulnerable to fire, cold, or acid. Finally the young men and women of several villages banded together, forming a militia almost two hundred people strong. The Aeger was surrounded and finally slain. Less than a dozen villagers survived, and they carved the Aeger's hide amongst themselves. Out of one of the pieces this armor was created.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Immunity to confusion
– Cold, Fire, and Acid Resistance: +15% (30% for barbarians)
– Physical damage resistance: +3% (barbarians only)
– Damage with halberds, staves, two-handed swords, and spears: +2 (barbarians only)

Armor Class: 3 (5 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 6 Strength

Weight: 35~

@8460 = ~Dark Lord Hertious, undead Warlord of Bane, wore this piece of armor for over five hundred years. During this time he was rumored to dwell in a castle somewhere within the Earthfast Mountains. How his armor moved to other lands without him is not certain, though the separation of the two was surely unpleasant.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Immunity to fear and panic

Combat abilities:
– Curse: Each hit has a 15% chance to curse living targets for 6 rounds, imposing a -1 penalty to all rolls, luck, Armor Class, and morale, and increasing their chances of critical misses by 5%. This effect does not stack.

Charge abilities:
– Cast Horror twice per day
  Special: All enemies within the area of effect when this spell is cast must save vs. Spell or flee in terror
  Duration: 1 turn

Armor Class: 0 (-4 vs. slashing, -3 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 15 Strength

Weight: 35~

@8470 = ~This plate mail has been expertly crafted. Sheathed in the chitinous scales of the ankheg, it provides a greater degree of protection than traditional plate mail and is not susceptible to rust. As any world-weary adventurer will tell you, however, the best appreciated aspect of ankheg mail is its light weight and low encumbrance. Monsters come and go, but fatigue is a constant enemy.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Acid Resistance: +20%

Armor Class: 1 (-2 vs. slashing, 0 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 8 Strength

Weight: 25~

@8480 = ~Named by Adarius Shin, the Doomplate is deserving of its foreboding title. He had hoped to strike fear in his enemies, but Adarius set a grim precedent when he mysteriously died soon after donning the suit, just as every adventurer who has worn it since has done. It might be said, however, that most adventurers die in their armor and are not known for their longevity.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Upon first equipping the armor, the wearer must make a saving throw vs. Death. Failing the save results in a permanent reduction of 1 point to both Constitution and saving throws vs. Death. If the save is successful, the armor instead grants a permanent bonus of 1 point to both Constitution and saving throws vs. Death. This effect becomes permanently bound to the wearer and will not transfer to anyone else, regardless of the outcome.

Armor Class: 0 (-3 vs. slashing)
Requires:
 12 Strength

Weight: 27~

@8490 = ~Few suits of armor in all the realms are the equal of this full plate. All that remains of the origin of the Hart are folktales and legends. The most popular of these is that an impossible battle was once fought against an army of orcs surging through the Three Trees Pass. Arngor of the Oak led the armies of men and elves, and it is said that he dueled with the orc commander till the sun set and the land was bathed in a bloody mist. Finally the orc fell, but Arngor had sustained wounds too vast for any to save him. His blood soaked through the armor he wore, infusing it with his courage and nobility. Thus the Armor of the Hart became known to men.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Every time the wearer is hit, there's a 5% chance it will be granted Armor of Faith (as per the spell) cast at level 10.
– All attack damage vs. evil is increased by 1

Charged abilities:
– Cast Bless, as per the priest spell, three times per day
  Duration: 6 rounds

– Cast Chant, as per the priest spell, once per day
  Duration: 1 turn

– Cast Aid at level 10 once per day
  Duration: 1 turn

Armor Class: -2 (-6 vs. slashing, -5 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 15 Strength

Weight: 45~

@8500 = ~This robe was fashioned for Hayes, the traitorous husband of Telana, soon after he discovered his talents as a wild mage. Very wealthy at the time, Hayes commissioned Halruaan wizards to craft it with silk, expensive dyes, and enchantments that would complement his unique talents.

Unfortunately, he wore it only twice: Its richness and clearly magical nature attracted the attention of the Red Wizards who soon pursued him. He gave up using magic unless it was absolutely necessary, hid the robe away, and started wearing a simple tunic. His wife salvaged the robe and passed it on to <CHARNAME>.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Permanent Chaos Shield on wearer
– Armor Class: +1 bonus
– Casting Speed: +1 bonus (wild mages only)

Weight: 3~

@8510 = ~Whether by design or through exposure to intense heat in battle, the chain links of this armor are coal black throughout. While legends usually speak of knights in shining armor facing great beasts, the fire resistant enchantment on this suit suggests equally great, if unheralded, battles with fire-breathing creatures.

